# iii Technical Conventions

- It is necessary to know iii's core primitives to properly architect software with it. They are [Functions, Triggers, and Workers](https://iii.dev/docs/primitives-and-concepts/functions-triggers-workers.mdx).
- When adapting existing codebases to use iii the preference should be towards using the conventions of the existing project
  and its libraries to create functionality that automatically registers these existing services with iii as Workers with
  Triggers and Functions.
- When adapting existing codebases the preference should always be to make as minimal of changes to the existing codebase as possible.
- Most iii Workers will be long-running processes however this might not always be the case and there may be times where
  the desired behavior is a Worker that exists temporarily and will `shutdown()` when it has completed its task.
  There may also be serverless functions which run as an HTTP endpoint and don't warrant being treated as a worker.
  Instead they can be registered as a function as described in the `registerFunction()` list item below.
- iii allows for any programming language to be used with it. This document uses camelCase but you should use
  the proper convention for the language being written (ex. `functionId` in node, `function_id` in python).
- iii uses `functionId` to identify functions. The basic convention is to create paths separated by `::`.
  They are suggested to be in the format of: `category::subcategory::action` (ex. `users::account::create`, `users::profile::update`).
  Prefer keeping depth to 3 segments; deeper or shallower nesting is allowed but should be justified.
  iii enforces only a single rule on `functionId`, the string cannot start with `iii::`. All other arbitrary strings are valid.
- iii's Workers run independently of iii. iii functions as the orchestration, observability, and interoperability layer.
- iii's Workers, Triggers, and Functions are able to dynamically register and unregister (Triggers and Functions) or shutdown (Workers) at any time.
- When creating new functionality adhere to iii's core functionality:
  - `trigger()`: Used for all code execution contexts. Takes a request object: `trigger({ function_id, payload })` to await
    a result. Use trigger actions to control delivery:
    - `TriggerAction.Enqueue({ queue })` — point-to-point async with config-driven retries and ordering. Queue behavior is defined in `iii-config.yaml`.
    - `TriggerAction.Void()` — fire-and-forget, no queue, no response.
    - For fan-out (one event, many consumers), use `trigger({ function_id: 'publish', payload: { topic, data } })` combined with `registerTrigger({ type: 'subscribe' })` on each consumer.
    The old `triggerVoid()` method no longer exists — use `TriggerAction.Void()` instead.
  - `registerTrigger()`: Used for defining when a function will be triggered: direct call via trigger(),
    http request, cron expressions, state updates, event subscriptions, and any other reactive context.
  - `registerFunction()`: Used for defining a function. Registering a function will make the iii engine aware
    of the function and as a result all of the Workers connected to iii will be able to call that function.
    Registered functions get a trigger automatically registered so that function can then be triggered by `functionId`.
    Anything that can receive data and optionally return data can be registered as a function provided the iii ecosystem supports it.
    For example, HTTP endpoints can be registered as functions, and once registered will behave as any other function.
  - `registerWorker()`: Used for initializing a Worker and connecting it to the iii engine. In Node, this replaces
    the old `init()` function. In Python, it replaces `III()` + `connect()`. The worker auto-connects on creation.
- iii's cron uses a 7 position expression: seconds, minutes, hours, day-of-month, month, day-of-week, year. Always use the 7-position format. Only use numeric expressions.
  Example: `0 30 9 * * 1-5 *` (weekdays at 9:30 AM, where 1=Mon through 5=Fri).
- Many basic patterns for iii are covered in the [HOWTO](https://iii.dev/docs/how-to) section of iii's docs.
  Complete reference material can be found in the [SDK Reference](https://iii.dev/docs/api-reference/iii-sdk),
  associated language-specific SDK pages, and [Modules](https://iii.dev/docs/modules) which explains additional functionality
  that iii's built-in Modules provide.
- In rare cases it may be necessary to implement a Module and its associated Adapter whenever desired functionality requires
  changing the core functionality and behavior of the iii engine. This is a rare case and requires the user to compile and maintain
  their own branch of iii. This should be avoided and explained carefully to the user. If the user insists then recommend to
  the user that they first open an Issue on the [iii repository](https://github.com/iii-hq/iii/issues) to see if it something
  the iii team is interested in placing on their roadmap.
